# recursive_decomposition.flow — corpus flow #19 of 20.
# See ../../../CORPUS_PLAN.md for the rubric this file is scored against.
#
# Shape stress test #3 of 4. This flow's purpose is to surface the
# RECURSIVE self-call shape — a flow that invokes itself with a
# narrower problem, with a base case (atomic task) and a depth budget
# bounding the tree. Recursion already surfaced ORGANICALLY at flow
# #14 (KYC, where a UBO may itself be a business and trigger a
# recursive KYC pass). Here it is the deliberate stress.
#
# Shape source: BabyAGI (Task Execution Agent + Task Creation Agent +
# Prioritization Agent; tasks continuously generated and refined
# based on progress; subtasks added to the queue as work proceeds).
# Tree of Thoughts (decomposition + generation + evaluation + search;
# tree depth bounded T ≤ 3, breadth bounded b ≤ 5; aggregation merges
# results from multiple reasoning paths). ReCAP recursive hierarchical
# decomposition. Anthropic's general "subagents" framing in Building
# Effective Agents (orchestrator dispatches to subagents that may
# themselves spawn further subagents).
#
# A recursive-decomposition workflow has this shape:
#
#   task in        receive a task with { description, depth_budget,
#                                         breadth_budget, parent_id }
#
#   classify       is this task ATOMIC (executable directly) or
#                  COMPLEX (needs further breakdown)?
#                    decision is itself a model call
#
#   atomic branch  if atomic OR depth_budget == 0:
#                    solve directly (search, call tool, compute)
#                    return Leaf { value, evidence }
#
#   complex branch if complex AND depth_budget > 0:
#                    decompose into [SubTask] (planner)
#                    cap to breadth_budget elements
#
#                    for each sub-task:
#                      RECURSE — call this same flow with
#                        depth_budget - 1, parent_id = current task id
#                      collect children: [TaskResult]
#
#                    aggregate children → Internal {
#                      synthesis, evidence, children,
#                      cost_cents: sum(children.cost) }
#
#   tree as data   the return value carries the entire tree —
#                  parent's result + array of child results
#                  recursively. The consumer can inspect the
#                  reasoning hierarchy, prune branches, re-execute
#                  failed sub-trees.
#
#   budgets        depth bound (tree depth ≤ N)
#                  breadth bound (children per node ≤ M)
#                  total wall-clock bound across the whole tree
#                  total cost bound across the whole tree
#                  Each bound is checked at every node; any breach
#                  collapses subsequent recursion to atomic-execute
#                  with what's known.
#
#   side effects   audit-log each task spawn (a node in the tree
#                  IS an audit-relevant event for explainable AI);
#                  emit progress events as nodes complete;
#                  persist intermediate results for the resumption
#                  case
#
# Three load-bearing facts:
#
#   (a) The flow must call itself. Not a structurally-similar
#       sibling flow — itself, with a narrower input. In current
#       Flow there is no syntax for this, and the resolver was not
#       designed for recursive flow references. The compilable stub
#       below CANNOT contain a recursive call; it has to delegate
#       the whole tree to an opaque tool that internally manages
#       recursion via its own task queue. The very thing the flow
#       exists to demonstrate is not expressible. Second organic
#       occurrence of #7 recursive-self-call (first: flow #14 KYC
#       UBOs).
#
#   (b) The return value is structurally recursive. TaskResult is
#       either a Leaf (atomic) carrying a value, or an Internal
#       node carrying a list of TaskResults — its children. This is
#       a RECURSIVE SUM TYPE: `TaskResult = Leaf | Internal {
#       children: [TaskResult] }`. The current type system has
#       record types with primitive fields and list types of
#       declared types, but no notion of variant types and no
#       notion of a type referring to itself. Encoding the
#       hierarchy as a flat list with parent_id pointers (the
#       compilable workaround below) loses the structural recursion
#       and pushes tree-walking into post-processing tools.
#
#   (c) Tree budgets compound across recursion. Total cost across
#       a 5-level deep tree with breadth 5 at each level is the
#       sum of cost across 5+5²+5³+5⁴+5⁵ = ~3900 LLM calls if
#       fully expanded. The flow needs cost-accumulation primitives
#       that survive across recursive invocations — i.e., shared
#       mutable state across the recursion. This is broader than
#       #8 expression ops alone — it is "accumulation across
#       recursive calls," which in functional languages is handled
#       by threading state explicitly through return values, and
#       in imperative languages by a shared accumulator. Current
#       Flow has neither.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Intended flow (NOT expressible in Flow today — uses recursive
# self-call):
#
#   flow decompose(TaskRequest) -> TaskResult {
#     classification = classify_task(it.description)
#
#     # base case: atomic, OR depth budget exhausted
#     if classification.kind == "atomic" or it.depth_budget == 0:
#       solved = solve_directly(it.description)
#       return Leaf { value: solved.value,
#                     evidence: solved.evidence,
#                     cost_cents: solved.cost_cents }
#
#     # decompose:
#     subtasks = plan_subtasks(it.description, it.breadth_budget)
#
#     # recurse — same flow, narrower input:
#     children = map(subtasks, st -> decompose(TaskRequest {
#       description:    st.description,
#       depth_budget:   it.depth_budget - 1,
#       breadth_budget: it.breadth_budget,
#       parent_id:      it.task_id,
#       task_id:        st.id,
#     }))
#
#     # aggregate children's results:
#     synthesis = synthesise(it.description, children)
#
#     Internal {
#       synthesis,
#       children,
#       cost_cents: sum_costs(children) + synthesis.cost_cents,
#     }
#   }
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Friction marks (per the CORPUS_PLAN rubric):
#
#   blocked: #7   sub-flow composition — PREDICTED. Specifically the
#                 RECURSIVE SELF-CALL sub-case. Second corpus
#                 occurrence (first: flow #14 KYC). The KYC case is
#                 "recursion because the data model is recursive";
#                 here it is "recursion because the algorithm is
#                 recursive." Both demand the same language feature:
#                 a flow can reference itself by name. Worth tracking
#                 as 7a (composition: flow calls a different flow) vs
#                 7b (self-recursion: flow calls itself). Both are
#                 unwritable; 7b has the additional question of
#                 termination guarantees.
#
#   blocked: #4   loops / fold over list — PREDICTED. 4a (map-fold
#                 over list, per Friday's recommended split) is
#                 dominant here: map over sub-tasks → recursive
#                 calls → list of child results, then fold to
#                 aggregate. Recurs from flows #4, #8, #15, #16,
#                 #17, #18 (across both 4a and 4b sub-shapes).
#
#   blocked: #11  sum types / variants — NINTH corpus occurrence.
#                 TWO new variant cases here:
#                 (1) Task = Atomic{description} | Complex{
#                     description, subtasks: [TaskRequest]}
#                 (2) TaskResult = Leaf{value, evidence, cost} |
#                     Internal{synthesis, children: [TaskResult],
#                              cost}
#                 Case (2) is the corpus's first occurrence of a
#                 RECURSIVE SUM TYPE — a variant that contains a
#                 list of itself. Distinct from the non-recursive
#                 variants of flows #10/#12/#13/#14/#15/#16/#17/
#                 #18 because the type-system question is harder
#                 (well-founded definition, termination of
#                 recursive matching). Worth flagging on Friday as
#                 a sub-finding under #11: not just "variants" but
#                 "recursive variants."
#
#   blocked: #1   multi-branch routing — atomic-vs-complex
#                 dispatch; budget-exhausted-vs-not dispatch;
#                 leaf-vs-internal at return.
#
#   blocked: #5   conditional binding — decompose ONLY if not
#                 atomic AND depth budget remaining; recurse ONLY
#                 if budgets allow; synthesise ONLY if any children
#                 returned successfully.
#
#   blocked: #3   in-source error handling — sub-task fails → mark
#                 that branch failed but continue with siblings
#                 (3b accumulation across the tree); planner fails
#                 → fall back to atomic execution (3a recovery).
#
#   blocked: #6   streaming / partial results — SIXTH organic
#                 corpus occurrence. Decomposition trees stream
#                 their structure to UIs as nodes complete; tools
#                 like the Anthropic Claude.ai "agents" UI show the
#                 tree filling in left-to-right, top-to-bottom in
#                 real time. The whole-tree-returned-at-end model
#                 cannot express this.
#
#   blocked: #8   string / numeric expression ops — sixth corpus
#                 occurrence. Cost accumulation across recursive
#                 calls (`sum_costs(children) + synthesis.cost`);
#                 depth-budget decrement (`it.depth_budget - 1`);
#                 breadth-budget check. Six distinct domains
#                 demanding expression ops at this point: time
#                 (flow #11), retrieval scoring (#13), SLO math
#                 (#15), merchandising weights (#16), refinement
#                 cost tracking (#18), recursion budgets (#19).
#
#   blocked: #10  optional types — synthesis absent on leaves;
#                 children empty list on leaves; evidence absent
#                 on certain failure modes; cost_cents zero
#                 sentinel is the workaround for "absent."
#
#   blocked: #12  time / scheduling — 12a deadlines: total wall-
#                 clock across the tree must bound; 12f durable
#                 execution: trees that explore for hours benefit
#                 from checkpointing (same gap as flow #17). For
#                 trees that exceed in-process time, the
#                 long-running shape is mandatory.
#
#   blocked: #13  Other: MANDATORY SIDE EFFECTS (slot #17,
#                 promoted at flow #17) — fifth occurrence.
#                 Audit-log each task spawn; emit progress event
#                 per node completion; persist intermediate results
#                 for explainability and re-execution.
#
#   blocked: #13  Other: SIDE-EFFECT IDEMPOTENCY — THIRD
#                 corpus occurrence (after flow #17 long_research
#                 and flow #18 iterative_refinement). On resume
#                 of a partially-completed tree, sub-trees that
#                 have already returned must not re-execute and
#                 must not re-fire their side effects (logging,
#                 cost-accounting, child-spawn). Three
#                 occurrences across three distinct domains clears
#                 the promotion threshold. PROMOTE before Friday
#                 to slot #18: "side-effect idempotency /
#                 exactly-once semantics on resume — the language
#                 must distinguish 'already committed' bindings
#                 from 'must re-fire' on resumption."
#
#   blocked: #14  lazy / short-circuit evaluation — fourteenth
#                 corpus occurrence. Skip decomposition past depth
#                 budget; skip child recursion once breadth budget
#                 hit; skip aggregation if all children failed.
#
#   blocked: #15  list-literal construction — twelfth occurrence.
#                 Empty children list on leaves; subtasks list
#                 from planner. Sub-finding from #18 (record-
#                 update / list-append within iterations) recurs
#                 here as the natural "append a child's result to
#                 the accumulating list" form.
#
#   blocked: #16  aggregation primitives — tenth occurrence.
#                 sum_costs across children; concat evidence
#                 lists; group_by sub-task kind for breadth
#                 analysis.
#
#   blocked: #13  Other: no string literals — task-kind enum,
#                 outcome enum.
#
#   shippable: N — the workflow that compiles below is structurally
#                  wrong for recursion. It has a single
#                  `decompose_recursively` tool that holds an
#                  internal queue and walks the tree. The Flow
#                  source describes "ask the oracle to solve this";
#                  it does NOT describe a decomposition strategy.
#                  An AI-safety reviewer looking for runaway-
#                  recursion protections in this source would find
#                  none — they all live inside the tool. For a
#                  language whose target audience is people who
#                  want to inspect what an agent system does, this
#                  is fundamentally broken.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Compilable stub: a single opaque tool that internally walks the
# entire tree. The flow self-call (the very thing the flow stresses)
# cannot be written; the recursive sum type cannot be expressed; the
# tree structure collapses to a flat list with parent_id pointers.

type TaskRequest    = { task_id:        string,
                      parent_id:      string,
                      description:    string,
                      depth_budget:   int,
                      breadth_budget: int,
                      wall_clock_budget_seconds: int,
                      cost_budget_cents:         int }

type TaskNode       = { task_id:     string,
                      parent_id:   string,
                      kind:        string,
                      synthesis:   string,
                      value:       string,
                      evidence:    [string],
                      cost_cents:  int,
                      depth:       int }

type TaskResult     = { root_task_id:    string,
                      status:          string,
                      total_cost_cents: int,
                      nodes:           [TaskNode],
                      final_synthesis: string }

tool decompose_recursively  (req: TaskRequest)            -> TaskResult
  effect model("decompose-v1")

flow decompose(TaskRequest) -> TaskResult {
  # workaround: the entire decomposition — recursion via flow self-
  # call, tree-as-data via recursive sum type, atomic-vs-complex
  # dispatch, depth/breadth/cost/time budget management, per-node
  # side effects (audit, progress emit, persistence),
  # idempotency-on-resume, child aggregation — collapses into one
  # opaque tool. The Flow source is one line. Every load-bearing
  # construct named in this file's friction marks is INSIDE the
  # tool, not visible from the workflow. For a stress test of
  # recursion, this is the maximum-degenerate stub.
  result = decompose_recursively(it)

  result
}
